The Israeli-Canadian architect continues to work on grand projects at a prodigious rate, while remaining an outspoken critic of the shortcomings and blind spots of current architectural practice.", "whotheyare": "Moshe Safdie's buildings -- from grand libraries to intimate apartment complexes -- explore the qualities of light and the nature of private and public space.", "whylisten": "

Moshe Safdie's master's thesis quickly became a cult building: his modular "Habitat '67" apartments for Montreal Expo '67. Within a dizzying pile of concrete, each apartment was carefully sited to have natural light and a tiny, private outdoor space for gardening. These themes have carried forward throughout Safdie's career -- his buildings tend to soak in the light, and to hold cozy, user-friendly spaces inside larger gestures.

He's a triple citizen of Canada, Israel and the United States, three places where the bulk of his buildings can be found: in Canada, the National Gallery in Ottawa, the Montreal Museum of Fine Arts, the Vancouver public library. For Yad Vashem, the Holocaust museum in Jerusalem, he designed the Children's Memorial and the Memorial to the Deportees; he's also built airport terminals in Tel Aviv. In the US, he designed the elegant and understated Peabody Essex Museum in Salem, Masachusetts, and the Crystal Bridges Museum in Arkansas.

aws-transcripts.transcript: So what? I'd like to talk about it. Something really dear to that was very dear to Kahn's heart, which is how do we discover what is really particular about a project? How do you discover the uniqueness of a project as unique as as a person? Because it seems to me that finding this uniqueness has to do with dealing with the whole force of globalization, that the particular is central to finding the uniqueness of place and the uniqueness of a program in the building. And so I'll take you to Wichita, Kansas, where I was at some years ago to do a science museum on a site right downtown by the river. And I thought the secret of the site is to make the building off the river part of the river. Unfortunately, though, the site was separated from the river by McLane's boulevard, so I suggested, Let's let's reroute McLane's and that gave birth instantly to friends of McLean Boulevard on it took six months to reroute it. The first image I showed the building committee waas this observatory last remark observatory the gentle mantra in Jaipur because I talked about what makes a building a building of science on it seemed to me that this structure complex, rich and yet totally rational it's an instrument had something to do with science. And somehow building for science should be different and unique and speak of that. And so my first sketch after left was to say, Let's cut the channel on DDE, make an island and make an island building. I got all excited, came back, and the sort of looked at me in this main said, an island. This used to be an island Ackerman Island, and we filled in the channel during the Depression to create jobs. And so the process began and they said, You can't put it all in an island. Some of it has to be on the mainland because we don't want to turn our back to the community. On Dhe, there emerged a designed the galleries sort of forming an island, and you could walk through them or on the roof. And there were all kinds of exciting features you could come in through the landside. Buildings work through the galleries into playgrounds in the landscape. If you were cheap, you could walk on top of a bridge for the roof, Peking the exhibits and then get totally seduced, come back and pay the $5 admission on the client was happy. What sort of happy? Because we were $4,000,000 over the budget, but essentially happy. But I was still troubled, and I was troubled because I felt this was capricious. It was complex, but there was something capricious about its complexity. It was what I would say compositional complexity, and I felt that if I had to fulfill what I talked about, a building for science, they had to be some kind of a generating ideas, some kind of a generating geometry. And this gave birth to the idea of having to royal generating geometry with its centre one with its center deep in the earth for the landside building and a tour oId with its center in the sky for the island building a tour oId for those who don't know is the surface of a doughnut or for some of us, a bagel on dhe out of this idea started spitting off many, many kind of variations off different plans and possibilities. And then the plan itself evolved in relationship to the exhibits and you see, you're the intersection of the plan with the total geometry and finally the building. This is the model. And when there were complaints about budget, I said, Well, it's worth doing the island because you get twice for your money reflections. And here is the building as it opened with a channel overlooking downtown and as seen from downtown and the bike routes going right through the building. So those traveling the river would see the exhibits and be drawn to the building. The two royal geometry made for very efficient building. Every beam in this building is the same radius, a laminated wood, every wall. Every concrete wall is resisting the stresses and supporting the building. Every piece of the building works. These are the galleries with a light coming in through the skylights and at night and on opening day. Going back to 1976. In 1976 was asked to design Children's Memorial Museum in the Holocaust Museum in the other. Shame in Jerusalem, which you see here, the campus and I was asked to do building and I was given all the artifacts of clothing and and drawings, and I felt very troubled. I worked on it for months, and I couldn't deal with it because I felt people coming out of the historic museum. They are totally saturated with information and to see yet another museum with information. It would make them just unable to digest. And so I made a counterproposal. I said, No building. There was a cave on the site. We tunnel into the hill, descend through the rock into an underground chamber. There's an anteroom with photographs of children who perished, and then you come into a large space. There is a single candle flickering in the center by an arrangement off reflective glasses.
